Typical usage (from command-line -- we have a gui now -- "python gui.py"):

1. uC sends (TMR0,voltage) pairs over uart; compile ../adc.cpp with
   DEFS=-DNDEBUG to get raw output.
2. serialport (~/usr/local/src/serialport) traps that data, storing it to
   a file.
3. adc2txt converts to human-readable form.
4. plots.py displays it.

E.g.

[Run this as long as you want to record data:]
$ ./serialport -r -b 38400 > ~/serial.out 2>&1 
$ ./serialport -r -b 38400 -x start
$ ./serialport -r -b 38400 -x <nchannels>
...wait a while...
$ ./serialport -r -b 38400 -x stop

$ cat ~/serial.out | ../AVR/adc/linux/adc2txt > adc.const.38400baud

$ python plots.py adc.const.38400baud 
